# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biofouling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Like surface tension, adsorption is a consequence of surface energy.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In a bulk material, all the bonding requirements (be they ionic, covalent, or metallic) of the constituent atoms of the material are fulfilled by other atoms in the material.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] However, atoms on the surface of the adsorbent are not wholly surrounded by other adsorbent atoms and therefore can attract adsorbates.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The exact nature of the bonding depends on the details of the species involved, but the adsorption process is generally classified as physisorption (characteristic of weak van der Waals forces) or chemisorption (characteristic of covalent bonding).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] It may also occur due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The nature of the adsorption can affect the structure of the adsorbed species.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] For example, polymer physisorption from solution can result in squashed structures on a surface.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Adsorption, ion exchange, and chromatography are sorption processes in which certain adsorbates are selectively transferred from the fluid phase to the surface of insoluble, rigid particles suspended in a vessel or packed in a column.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Pharmaceutical industry applications, which use adsorption as a means to prolong neurological exposure to specific drugs or parts thereof, are lesser known.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The word "adsorption" was coined in 1881 by German physicist Heinrich Kayser (1853–1940).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The adsorption of gases and solutes is usually described through isotherms, that is, the amount of adsorbate on the adsorbent as a function of its pressure (if gas) or concentration (for liquid phase solutes) at constant temperature.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The quantity adsorbed is nearly always normalized by the mass of the adsorbent to allow comparison of different materials.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] A number of different isotherm models have been developed.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] where x is the mass of adsorbate adsorbed, m is the mass of the adsorbent, P is the pressure of adsorbate (this can be changed to concentration if investigating solution rather than gas), and k and n are empirical constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The function is not adequate at very high pressure because in reality $x/m$ has an asymptotic maximum as pressure increases without bound.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] As the temperature increases, the constants k and n change to reflect the empirical observation that the quantity adsorbed rises more slowly and higher pressures are required to saturate the surface.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Irving Langmuir was the first to derive a scientifically based adsorption isotherm in 1918.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The model applies to gases adsorbed on solid surfaces.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] It is a semi-empirical isotherm with a kinetic basis and was derived based on statistical thermodynamics.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] It is the most common isotherm equation to use due to its simplicity and its ability to fit a variety of adsorption data.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The surface is energetically homogeneous, and adsorbed molecules do not interact.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] At the maximum adsorption, only a monolayer is formed.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Adsorption only occurs on localized sites on the surface, not with other adsorbates.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] These four assumptions are seldom all true: there are always imperfections on the surface, adsorbed molecules are not necessarily inert, and the mechanism is clearly not the same for the first molecules to adsorb to a surface as for the last.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The fourth condition is the most troublesome, as frequently more molecules will adsorb to the monolayer; this problem is addressed by the BET isotherm for relatively flat (non-microporous) surfaces.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is nonetheless the first choice for most models of adsorption and has many applications in surface kinetics (usually called Langmuir–Hinshelwood kinetics) and thermodynamics.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Langmuir suggested that adsorption takes place through this mechanism: $A_{\text{g}}+S\rightleftharpoons AS$ , where *A* is a gas molecule, and *S* is an adsorption site.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The direct and inverse rate constants are *k* and *k*−1.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] where P is the partial pressure of the gas or the molar concentration of the solution.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] For very low pressures $\theta \approx KP$ , and for high pressures $\theta \approx 1$ .
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The value of $\theta$ is difficult to measure experimentally; usually, the adsorbate is a gas and the quantity adsorbed is given in moles, grams, or gas volumes at standard temperature and pressure (STP) per gram of adsorbent.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Through its slope and *y* intercept we can obtain *v*mon and *K*, which are constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] *v*mon is related to the number of adsorption sites through the ideal gas law.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] If we assume that the number of sites is just the whole area of the solid divided into the cross section of the adsorbate molecules, we can easily calculate the surface area of the adsorbent.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The surface area of an adsorbent depends on its structure: the more pores it has, the greater the area, which has a big influence on reactions on surfaces.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] where *i* is each one of the gases that adsorb.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] 1) To choose between the Langmuir and Freundlich equations, the enthalpies of adsorption must be investigated.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] While the Langmuir model assumes that the energy of adsorption remains constant with surface occupancy, the Freundlich equation is derived with the assumption that the heat of adsorption continually decrease as the binding sites are occupied.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The choice of the model based on best fitting of the data is a common misconception.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] 2) The use of the linearized form of the Langmuir model is no longer common practice.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Advances in computational power allowed for nonlinear regression to be performed quickly and with higher confidence since no data transformation is required.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Often molecules do form multilayers, that is, some are adsorbed on already adsorbed molecules, and the Langmuir isotherm is not valid.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In 1938 Stephen Brunauer, Paul Emmett, and Edward Teller developed a model isotherm that takes that possibility into account.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Their theory is called BET theory, after the initials in their last names.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The derivation of the formula is more complicated than Langmuir's (see links for complete derivation).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The key assumption used in deriving the BET equation that the successive heats of adsorption for all layers except the first are equal to the heat of condensation of the adsorbate.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is usually better for chemisorption, and the BET isotherm works better for physisorption for non-microporous surfaces.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In other instances, molecular interactions between gas molecules previously adsorbed on a solid surface form significant interactions with gas molecules in the gaseous phases.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Hence, adsorption of gas molecules to the surface is more likely to occur around gas molecules that are already present on the solid surface, rendering the Langmuir adsorption isotherm ineffective for the purposes of modelling.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This effect was studied in a system where nitrogen was the adsorbate and tungsten was the adsorbent by Paul Kisliuk (1922–2008) in 1957.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] To compensate for the increased probability of adsorption occurring around molecules present on the substrate surface, Kisliuk developed the precursor state theory, whereby molecules would enter a precursor state at the interface between the solid adsorbent and adsorbate in the gaseous phase.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] From here, adsorbate molecules would either adsorb to the adsorbent or desorb into the gaseous phase.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The probability of adsorption occurring from the precursor state is dependent on the adsorbate's proximity to other adsorbate molecules that have already been adsorbed.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] If an adsorbate molecule enters the precursor state at a location that is remote from any other previously adsorbed adsorbate molecules, the sticking probability is reflected by the size of the SD constant.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] As SD is dictated by factors that are taken into account by the Langmuir model, SD can be assumed to be the adsorption rate constant.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] However, the rate constant for the Kisliuk model (*R*') is different from that of the Langmuir model, as *R*' is used to represent the impact of diffusion on monolayer formation and is proportional to the square root of the system's diffusion coefficient.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] As can be seen in the formula, the variation of *K* must be isosteric, that is, at constant coverage.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] that is to say, adsorption is more exothermic than liquefaction.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The adsorption of ensemble molecules on a surface or interface can be divided into two processes: adsorption and desorption.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] If the adsorption rate wins the desorption rate, the molecules will accumulate over time giving the adsorption curve over time.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] If the desorption rate is larger, the number of molecules on the surface will decrease over time.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The adsorption rate is dependent on the temperature, the diffusion rate of the solute (related to mean free path for pure gas), and the energy barrier between the molecule and the surface.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The diffusion and key elements of the adsorption rate can be calculated using Fick's laws of diffusion and the Einstein relation (kinetic theory).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] where A is the surface area (unit m2), C is the number concentration of the molecule in the bulk solution (unit #/m3), D is the diffusion constant (unit m2/s), and t is time (unit s).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Further simulations and analysis of this equation show that the square root dependence on the time is originated from the decrease of the concentrations near the surface under ideal adsorption conditions.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Also, this equation only works for the beginning of the adsorption when a well-behaved concentration gradient forms near the surface.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Correction on the reduction of the adsorption area and slowing down of the concentration gradient evolution have to be considered over a longer time.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Under real experimental conditions, the flow and the small adsorption area always make the adsorption rate faster than what this equation predicted, and the energy barrier will either accelerate this rate by surface attraction or slow it down by surface repulsion.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Thus, the prediction from this equation is often a few to several orders of magnitude away from the experimental results.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The desorption of a molecule from the surface depends on the binding energy of the molecule to the surface and the temperature.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The typical overall adsorption rate is thus often a combined result of the adsorption and desorption.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Since 1980 two theories were worked on to explain adsorption and obtain equations that work.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] These two are referred to as the chi hypothesis, the quantum mechanical derivation, and excess surface work (ESW).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] where "ads" stands for "adsorbed", "m" stands for "monolayer equivalence" and "vap" is reference to the vapor pressure of the liquid adsorptive at the same temperature as the solid sample.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The plot of $n_{ads}$ adsorbed versus $\chi$ is referred to as the chi plot.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] For flat surfaces, the slope of the chi plot yields the surface area.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Empirically, this plot was noticed as being a very good fit to the isotherm by Michael Polanyi and also by Jan Hendrik de Boer and Cornelis Zwikker but not pursued.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This was due to criticism in the former case by Albert Einstein and in the latter case by Brunauer.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This flat surface equation may be used as a "standard curve" in the normal tradition of comparison curves, with the exception that the porous sample's early portion of the plot of $n_{ads}$ versus $\chi$ acts as a self-standard.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Ultramicroporous, microporous, and mesoporous conditions may be analyzed using this technique.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Typical standard deviations for full isotherm fits including porous samples are less than 2%.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Notice that in this description of physical adsorption, the entropy of adsorption is consistent with the Dubinin thermodynamic criterion, that is the entropy of adsorption from the liquid state to the adsorbed state is approximately zero.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Adsorbents are used usually in the form of spherical pellets, rods, moldings, or monoliths with a hydrodynamic radius between 0.25 and 5 millimetres (0.0098 and 0.1969 in).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] They must have high abrasion resistance, high thermal stability, and small pore diameters, which results in higher exposed surface area and hence high capacity for adsorption.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The adsorbents must also have a distinct pore structure that enables fast transport of the gaseous vapors.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Silica gel is a chemically inert, non-toxic, polar, and dimensionally stable (< 400 °C or 750 °F) amorphous form of SiO2.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] It is prepared by the reaction between sodium silicate and acetic acid, which is followed by a series of after-treatment processes such as aging, pickling, etc.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] These after-treatment methods results in various pore size distributions.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Silica is used for drying of process air (e.g. oxygen, natural gas) and adsorption of heavy (polar) hydrocarbons from natural gas.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Zeolites are natural or synthetic crystalline aluminosilicates, which have a repeating pore network and release water at high temperature.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] They are manufactured by hydrothermal synthesis of sodium aluminosilicate or another silica source in an autoclave followed by ion exchange with certain cations (Na+, Li+, Ca2+, K+, NH4+).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The channel diameter of zeolite cages usually ranges from 2 to 9 Å.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The ion exchange process is followed by drying of the crystals, which can be pelletized with a binder to form macroporous pellets.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Zeolites are applied in drying of process air, CO2 removal from natural gas, CO removal from reforming gas, air separation, catalytic cracking, and catalytic synthesis and reforming.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Non-polar (siliceous) zeolites are synthesized from aluminum-free silica sources or by dealumination of aluminum-containing zeolites.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The dealumination process is done by treating the zeolite with steam at elevated temperatures, typically greater than 500 °C (930 °F).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This high-temperature heat treatment breaks the aluminum-oxygen bonds and the aluminum atom is expelled from the zeolite framework.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The term "adsorption" itself was coined by Heinrich Kayser in 1881 in the context of uptake of gases by carbons.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Activated carbon is a highly porous, amorphous solid consisting of microcrystallites with a graphite lattice, usually prepared in small pellets or a powder.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] One of its main drawbacks is that it reacts with oxygen at moderate temperatures (over 300 °C (572 °F)).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Activated carbon can be manufactured from carbonaceous material, including coal (bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite), peat, wood, or nutshells (e.g., coconut).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The manufacturing process consists of two phases: carbonization and activation.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The carbonization process includes drying and then heating to separate by-products, including tars and other hydrocarbons from the raw material, as well as to drive off any gases generated.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The process is completed by heating the material over 400 °C (750 °F) in an oxygen-free atmosphere that cannot support combustion.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The carbonized particles are then "activated" by exposing them to an oxidizing agent, usually steam or carbon dioxide, at high temperature.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This agent burns off the pore-blocking structures created during the carbonization phase, and so they develop a porous, three-dimensional graphite lattice structure.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The size of the pores developed during activation is a function of the time that they spend in this stage.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Longer exposure times result in larger pore sizes.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The most popular aqueous phase carbons are bituminous based because of their hardness, abrasion resistance, pore size distribution, and low cost, but their effectiveness needs to be tested in each application to determine the optimal product.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Activated carbon is used for adsorption of organic substances and non-polar adsorbates and it is also usually used for waste gas (and waste water) treatment.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] It is the most widely used adsorbent since most of its chemical (e.g. surface groups) and physical properties (e.g. pore size distribution and surface area) can be tuned according to what is needed.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Its usefulness also derives from its large micropore (and sometimes mesopore) volume and the resulting high surface area.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Recent research works reported activated carbon as an effective agent to adsorb cationic species of toxic metals from multi-pollutant systems and also proposed possible adsorption mechanisms with supporting evidences.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The adsorption of water at surfaces is of broad importance in chemical engineering, materials science, and catalysis.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Also termed surface hydration, the presence of physically or chemically adsorbed water at the surfaces of solids plays an important role in governing interface properties, chemical reaction pathways, and catalytic performance in a wide range of systems.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In the case of physically adsorbed water, surface hydration can be eliminated simply through drying at conditions of temperature and pressure allowing full vaporization of water.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The low cost ($200/ton) and high cycle rate (2,000 ×) of synthetic zeolites such as Linde 13X with water adsorbate has garnered much academic and commercial interest recently for use for thermal energy storage (TES), specifically of low-grade solar and waste heat.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Several pilot projects have been funded in the EU from 2000 to the present (2020).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The basic concept is to store solar thermal energy as chemical latent energy in the zeolite.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Typically, hot dry air from flat plate solar collectors is made to flow through a bed of zeolite such that any water adsorbate present is driven off.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Storage can be diurnal, weekly, monthly, or even seasonal depending on the volume of the zeolite and the area of the solar thermal panels.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] When heat is called for during the night, or sunless hours, or winter, humidified air flows through the zeolite.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] As the humidity is adsorbed by the zeolite, heat is released to the air and subsequently to the building space.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This form of TES, with specific use of zeolites, was first taught by John Guerra in 1978.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Typical adsorbents proposed for carbon capture and storage are zeolites and MOFs.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The customization of adsorbents makes them a potentially attractive alternative to absorption.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Because adsorbents can be regenerated by temperature or pressure swing, this step can be less energy intensive than absorption regeneration methods.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Major problems that are present with adsorption cost in carbon capture are: regenerating the adsorbent, mass ratio, solvent/MOF, cost of adsorbent, production of the adsorbent, lifetime of adsorbent.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In sorption enhanced water gas shift (SEWGS) technology a pre-combustion carbon capture process, based on solid adsorption, is combined with the water-gas shift reaction (WGS) in order to produce a high pressure hydrogen stream.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The CO2 stream produced can be stored or used for other industrial processes.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Protein adsorption is a process that has a fundamental role in the field of biomaterials.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Indeed, biomaterial surfaces in contact with biological media, such as blood or serum, are immediately coated by proteins.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Therefore, living cells do not interact directly with the biomaterial surface, but with the adsorbed proteins layer.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This protein layer mediates the interaction between biomaterials and cells, translating biomaterial physical and chemical properties into a "biological language".
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In fact, cell membrane receptors bind to protein layer bioactive sites and these receptor-protein binding events are transduced, through the cell membrane, in a manner that stimulates specific intracellular processes that then determine cell adhesion, shape, growth, and differentiation.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Protein adsorption is influenced by many surface properties such as surface wettability, surface chemical composition, and surface nanometre-scale morphology.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Surfactant adsorption is a similar phenomenon, but utilising surfactant molecules in the place of proteins.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Combining an adsorbent with a refrigerant, adsorption chillers use heat to provide a cooling effect.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This heat, in the form of hot water, may come from any number of industrial sources including waste heat from industrial processes, prime heat from solar thermal installations or from the exhaust or water jacket heat of a piston engine or turbine.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Although there are similarities between adsorption chillers and absorption refrigeration, the former is based on the interaction between gases and solids.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The adsorption chamber of the chiller is filled with a solid material (for example zeolite, silica gel, alumina, active carbon or certain types of metal salts), which in its neutral state has adsorbed the refrigerant.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] When heated, the solid desorbs (releases) refrigerant vapour, which subsequently is cooled and liquefied.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This liquid refrigerant then provides a cooling effect at the evaporator from its enthalpy of vaporization.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In the final stage the refrigerant vapour is (re)adsorbed into the solid.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] As an adsorption chiller requires no compressor, it is relatively quiet.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Portal site mediated adsorption is a model for site-selective activated gas adsorption in metallic catalytic systems that contain a variety of different adsorption sites.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In such systems, low-coordination "edge and corner" defect-like sites can exhibit significantly lower adsorption enthalpies than high-coordination (basal plane) sites.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] As a result, these sites can serve as "portals" for very rapid adsorption to the rest of the surface.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The phenomenon relies on the common "spillover" effect (described below), where certain adsorbed species exhibit high mobility on some surfaces.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The model explains seemingly inconsistent observations of gas adsorption thermodynamics and kinetics in catalytic systems where surfaces can exist in a range of coordination structures, and it has been successfully applied to bimetallic catalytic systems where synergistic activity is observed.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In contrast to pure spillover, portal site adsorption refers to surface diffusion to adjacent adsorption sites, not to non-adsorptive support surfaces.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The model appears to have been first proposed for carbon monoxide on silica-supported platinum by Brandt *et al.* (1993).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] A similar, but independent model was developed by King and co-workers to describe hydrogen adsorption on silica-supported alkali promoted ruthenium, silver-ruthenium, and copper-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The same group applied the model to CO hydrogenation (Fischer–Tropsch synthesis).
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Zupanc *et al.* (2002) subsequently confirmed the same model for hydrogen adsorption on magnesia-supported caesium-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Trens *et al.* (2009) have similarly described CO surface diffusion on carbon-supported Pt particles of varying morphology.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The presence of the metal serves as a lower-energy pathway for gaseous species to first adsorb to the metal and then diffuse on the support surface.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] This is possible because the adsorbed species attains a lower energy state once it has adsorbed to the metal, thus lowering the activation barrier between the gas phase species and the support-adsorbed species.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Hydrogen spillover is the most common example of an adsorptive spillover.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] In the case of hydrogen, adsorption is most often accompanied with dissociation of molecular hydrogen (H2) to atomic hydrogen (H), followed by spillover of the hydrogen atoms present.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The spillover effect has been used to explain many observations in heterogeneous catalysis and adsorption.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Adsorption of molecules onto polymer surfaces is central to a number of applications, including development of non-stick coatings and in various biomedical devices.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Polymers may also be adsorbed to surfaces through polyelectrolyte adsorption.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Adsorption is the beginning of viral entry, which is the earliest stage of infection in the viral life cycle.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The next steps are penetration, uncoating, synthesis (transcription if needed, and translation), and release.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The virus replication cycle, in this respect, is similar for all types of viruses.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Factors such as transcription may or may not be needed if the virus is able to integrate its genomic information in the cell's nucleus, or if the virus can replicate itself directly within the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] The game of *Tetris* is a puzzle game in which blocks of 4 are adsorbed onto a surface during game play.
[src:biofouling/adsorption] Scientists have used *Tetris* blocks "as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape" and their "adsorption on a flat surface" for studying the thermodynamics of nanoparticles.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae are polyphyletic as they do not share a common ancestor.
[src:biofouling/alga] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:biofouling/alga] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:biofouling/alga] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:biofouling/alga] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:biofouling/alga] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:biofouling/alga] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:biofouling/alga] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:biofouling/alga] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:biofouling/alga] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:biofouling/alga] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:biofouling/alga] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:biofouling/alga] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:biofouling/alga] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:biofouling/alga] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:biofouling/alga] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:biofouling/alga] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:biofouling/alga] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:biofouling/alga] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:biofouling/alga] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:biofouling/alga] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:biofouling/alga] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:biofouling/alga] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:biofouling/alga] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:biofouling/alga] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:biofouling/alga] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:biofouling/alga] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:biofouling/alga] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:biofouling/alga] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:biofouling/alga] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:biofouling/alga] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:biofouling/alga] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:biofouling/alga] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:biofouling/alga] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:biofouling/alga] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:biofouling/alga] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:biofouling/alga] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:biofouling/alga] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:biofouling/alga] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:biofouling/alga] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:biofouling/alga] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:biofouling/alga] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:biofouling/alga] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:biofouling/alga] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:biofouling/alga] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:biofouling/alga] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:biofouling/alga] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:biofouling/alga] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:biofouling/alga] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:biofouling/alga] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:biofouling/alga] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:biofouling/alga] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:biofouling/alga] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:biofouling/alga] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:biofouling/alga] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:biofouling/alga] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:biofouling/alga] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:biofouling/alga] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:biofouling/alga] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:biofouling/alga] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:biofouling/alga] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:biofouling/alga] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:biofouling/alga] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:biofouling/alga] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:biofouling/alga] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:biofouling/alga] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:biofouling/alga] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:biofouling/alga] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:biofouling/alga] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:biofouling/alga] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:biofouling/alga] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:biofouling/alga] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:biofouling/alga] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:biofouling/alga] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:biofouling/alga] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:biofouling/alga] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:biofouling/alga] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:biofouling/alga] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:biofouling/alga] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:biofouling/alga] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:biofouling/alga] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:biofouling/alga] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:biofouling/alga] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:biofouling/alga] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:biofouling/alga] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:biofouling/alga] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:biofouling/alga] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:biofouling/alga] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:biofouling/alga] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:biofouling/alga] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:biofouling/alga] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:biofouling/alga] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:biofouling/alga] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:biofouling/alga] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:biofouling/alga] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:biofouling/alga] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:biofouling/alga] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:biofouling/alga] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:biofouling/alga] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:biofouling/alga] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:biofouling/alga] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:biofouling/alga] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:biofouling/alga] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:biofouling/alga] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:biofouling/alga] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:biofouling/alga] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:biofouling/alga] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:biofouling/alga] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:biofouling/alga] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:biofouling/alga] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:biofouling/alga] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:biofouling/alga] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:biofouling/alga] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:biofouling/alga] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:biofouling/alga] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:biofouling/alga] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:biofouling/alga] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:biofouling/alga] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:biofouling/alga] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:biofouling/alga] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:biofouling/alga] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:biofouling/alga] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:biofouling/alga] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:biofouling/alga] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:biofouling/alga] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:biofouling/alga] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:biofouling/alga] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:biofouling/alga] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:biofouling/alga] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:biofouling/alga] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:biofouling/alga] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:biofouling/alga] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:biofouling/alga] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:biofouling/alga] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:biofouling/alga] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:biofouling/alga] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:biofouling/alga] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:biofouling/alga] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:biofouling/alga] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:biofouling/alga] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:biofouling/alga] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:biofouling/alga] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:biofouling/alga] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:biofouling/alga] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:biofouling/alga] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:biofouling/alga] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:biofouling/alga] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:biofouling/alga] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:biofouling/alga] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:biofouling/alga] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:biofouling/alga] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:biofouling/alga] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:biofouling/alga] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:biofouling/alga] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:biofouling/alga] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:biofouling/alga] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:biofouling/alga] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:biofouling/alga] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:biofouling/alga] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:biofouling/alga] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:biofouling/alga] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:biofouling/alga] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:biofouling/alga] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:biofouling/alga] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:biofouling/alga] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:biofouling/alga] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:biofouling/alga] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:biofouling/alga] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:biofouling/alga] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:biofouling/alga] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:biofouling/alga] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:biofouling/alga] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:biofouling/alga] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:biofouling/alga] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:biofouling/alga] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:biofouling/alga] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:biofouling/alga] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:biofouling/alga] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:biofouling/alga] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:biofouling/alga] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:biofouling/alga] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:biofouling/alga] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:biofouling/alga] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:biofouling/alga] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:biofouling/alga] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:biofouling/alga] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:biofouling/alga] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:biofouling/alga] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:biofouling/alga] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:biofouling/alga] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:biofouling/alga] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:biofouling/alga] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:biofouling/alga] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:biofouling/alga] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:biofouling/alga] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:biofouling/alga] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:biofouling/alga] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:biofouling/alga] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:biofouling/alga] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:biofouling/alga] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:biofouling/alga] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:biofouling/alga] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:biofouling/alga] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:biofouling/alga] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:biofouling/alga] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:biofouling/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:biofouling/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:biofouling/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:biofouling/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:biofouling/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:biofouling/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:biofouling/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:biofouling/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:biofouling/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:biofouling/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:biofouling/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:biofouling/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:biofouling/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:biofouling/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:biofouling/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:biofouling/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:biofouling/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:biofouling/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:biofouling/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:biofouling/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:biofouling/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:biofouling/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:biofouling/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:biofouling/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:biofouling/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:biofouling/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:biofouling/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:biofouling/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:biofouling/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:biofouling/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:biofouling/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:biofouling/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:biofouling/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:biofouling/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:biofouling/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:biofouling/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:biofouling/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:biofouling/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:biofouling/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:biofouling/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:biofouling/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:biofouling/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:biofouling/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:biofouling/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:biofouling/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:biofouling/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:biofouling/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:biofouling/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:biofouling/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:biofouling/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:biofouling/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:biofouling/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:biofouling/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:biofouling/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:biofouling/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:biofouling/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:biofouling/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:biofouling/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:biofouling/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:biofouling/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:biofouling/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:biofouling/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:biofouling/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:biofouling/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:biofouling/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:biofouling/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:biofouling/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:biofouling/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:biofouling/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:biofouling/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:biofouling/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:biofouling/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:biofouling/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:biofouling/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:biofouling/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:biofouling/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:biofouling/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:biofouling/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:biofouling/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:biofouling/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:biofouling/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:biofouling/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:biofouling/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:biofouling/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:biofouling/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:biofouling/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:biofouling/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:biofouling/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:biofouling/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biofouling/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biofouling/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:biofouling/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:biofouling/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:biofouling/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:biofouling/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biofouling/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biofouling/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:biofouling/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:biofouling/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:biofouling/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:biofouling/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:biofouling/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:biofouling/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:biofouling/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:biofouling/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:biofouling/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:biofouling/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:biofouling/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:biofouling/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:biofouling/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:biofouling/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:biofouling/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:biofouling/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:biofouling/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:biofouling/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:biofouling/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:biofouling/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:biofouling/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:biofouling/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:biofouling/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:biofouling/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:biofouling/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:biofouling/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:biofouling/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:biofouling/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:biofouling/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:biofouling/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:biofouling/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:biofouling/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:biofouling/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:biofouling/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:biofouling/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:biofouling/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:biofouling/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:biofouling/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:biofouling/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:biofouling/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:biofouling/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:biofouling/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:biofouling/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:biofouling/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:biofouling/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:biofouling/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:biofouling/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:biofouling/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:biofouling/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:biofouling/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:biofouling/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:biofouling/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:biofouling/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:biofouling/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:biofouling/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:biofouling/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:biofouling/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:biofouling/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:biofouling/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:biofouling/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:biofouling/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:biofouling/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] The ***Annual Review of Materials Research*** is a peer-reviewed journal that publishes review articles about materials science.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] It has been published by the nonprofit Annual Reviews since 1971, when it was first released under the title the ***Annual Review of Materials Science***.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] Four people have served as editors, with the current editor Ram Seshadri stepping into the position in 2024.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] As of 2023, it is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal a 2024 impact factor of 10.4.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] The *Annual Review of Materials Science* was first published in 1971 by the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews, making it their sixteenth journal.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] In 2001, its name was changed to the current form, the *Annual Review of Materials Research*.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] The name change was intended "to better reflect the broad appeal that materials research has for so many diverse groups of scientists and not simply those who identify themselves with the academic discipline of materials science." As of 2020, it was published both in print and electronically.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] It defines its scope as covering significant developments in the field of materials science, including methodologies for studying materials and materials phenomena.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal a 2024 impact factor of 10.4 ranking it fifty-seventh of 460 titles in the category "Materials Science, Multidisciplinary".
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, Civil Engineering Abstracts, INSPEC, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] The *Annual Review of Materials Research* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] The editor is assisted by the editorial committee, which includes associate editors, regular members, and occasionally guest editors.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] Guest members participate at the invitation of the editor, and serve terms of one year.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] All other members of the editorial committee are appointed by the Annual Reviews board of directors and serve five-year terms.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] The editorial committee determines which topics should be included in each volume and solicits reviews from qualified authors.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] Unsolicited manuscripts are not accepted.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] Peer review of accepted manuscripts is undertaken by the editorial committee.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] Dates indicate publication years in which someone was credited as a lead editor or co-editor of a journal volume.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] The planning process for a volume begins well before the volume appears, so appointment to the position of lead editor generally occurred prior to the first year shown here.
[src:biofouling/annual-review-of-materials-research] An editor who has retired or died may be credited as a lead editor of a volume that they helped to plan, even if it is published after their retirement or death.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Although commonly discussed as being applied to ships, antifouling paints are also of benefit in many other sectors such as off-shore structures and fish farms.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] In the Age of Sail, sailing vessels suffered severely from the growth of barnacles and weeds on the hull, called "fouling".
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Starting in the mid-1700s thin sheets of copper and approximately 100 years later, Muntz metal, were nailed onto the hull in an attempt to prevent marine growth.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] One famous example of the traditional use of metal sheathing is the clipper *Cutty Sark*, which is preserved as a museum ship in dry-dock at Greenwich in England.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] While anti-fouling coatings began to be developed from 1840 onwards, the first practical commercial anti-fouling coatings were established around 1860.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] One of the first successful commercial patents was for 'McIness', a metallic soap compound with copper sulphate that was applied heated over a quick-drying rosin varnish primer with an iron oxide pigment.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] The Bonnington Chemical Works began marketing copper sulphide anti-fouling paint around 1850.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Other widely used anti-fouling paints were developed in the late 19th century, with some 213 anti-fouling patents being recorded by 1872.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Among the most widely used in the 1880s and 1890s was a hot plastic composition known as Italian Morovian.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] In an official 1900 Letter from the U.S.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] However, once an antifouling paint "with very fair results" was found, the iron ships were instead retained and continued to be built.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] During World War II, which included a substantial naval component, the U.S.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Navy provided significant funding to the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution to gather information and conduct research on marine biofouling and technologies for its prevention.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] This work was published as a book in 1952, the contents of which are available online as individual chapters.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] The third and final part of this book includes a number of chapters that go into the state of the art at that time for the formulation of anti-fouling paints.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] In modern times, antifouling paints are formulated with cuprous oxide (or other copper compounds) and/or other biocides—special chemicals which impede growth of barnacles, algae, and marine organisms.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Historically, copper paints were red, leading to ship bottoms still being painted red today.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] "Soft", or ablative bottom paints slowly slough off in the water, releasing a copper or zinc based biocide into the water column.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] The movement of water increases the rate of this action.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Ablative paints are widely used on the hulls of recreational vessels and typically are reapplied every 1–3 years.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] "Contact leaching" paints "create a porous film on the surface.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Biocides are held in the pores, and released slowly." Another type of hard bottom paint includes Teflon and silicone coatings which are too slippery for growth to stick.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] SealCoat systems, which must be professionally applied, dry with small fibers sticking out from the coating surface.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] These small fibers move in the water, preventing bottom growth from adhering.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Now that tributyltin has been banned, the most commonly used anti-fouling bottom paints are copper-based.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Copper-based antifouling paints can also have adverse effects on marine organisms.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Copper occurs naturally in aquatic systems but can build up in ports or marinas where there are lots of boats.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Copper can leach out of anti-fouling paint from the hulls of the boats or fall off the hulls in different sized paint particles.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] This can lead to higher-than-normal concentrations of copper in the ports or bays.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] This excess of copper in the marine ecosystem can have adverse effects on the marine environment and its organisms.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] In marinas, the river nerite, a brackish water snail, was found to have higher mortality, negative growth, and a large decrease in reproduction compared to areas with no boating.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] The snails in marinas had more tissue (histopathological) issues and alterations in areas like their gills and gonads as well.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Increased exposure to copper from antifouling paint has also been found to decrease enzyme activity in brine shrimp.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Antifouling paint particles can be eaten by zooplankton or other marine species and move up the food chain, bioaccumulating in fish.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] This accumulation of copper through the food web can cause damage to not only the species eating the particle, but those that are accumulating it in their tissues from their diet.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Antifouling paint particles can also end up in the sediment of harbors or bays and damage the benthic environment or the organisms that live in them.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] These are the known effects of copper based antifouling paint; however, it has not been a large focus of study so the extent of the effects is not fully known.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] More research is needed to fully understand how these paints and the metals in them affect their environments.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] The Port of San Diego is investigating how to reduce copper input from copper-based antifouling coatings, and Washington State has passed a law which may phase in a ban on copper antifouling coatings on recreational vessels beginning in January 2018.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] However, despite the toxic chemistry of bottom paint and its accumulation in water ways across the globe, a similar ban was rescinded in the Netherlands after the European Union's Scientific Committee on Health and Environmental Risks concluded The Hague had insufficiently justified the law.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] "Sloughing bottom paints", or "ablative" paints, are an older type of paint designed to create a hull coating which ablates (wears off) slowly, exposing a fresh layer of biocides.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Scrubbing a hull with sloughing bottom paint while it is in the water releases its biocides into the environment.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] One way to reduce the environmental impact from hulls with sloughing bottom paint is to have them hauled out and cleaned at boatyards with a "closed loop" system.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] Some innovative bottom paints that do not rely on copper or tin have been developed in response to the increasing scrutiny that copper-based ablative bottom paints have received as environmental pollutants.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] A possible future replacement for antifouling paint may be slime.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] A mesh would cover a ship's hull beneath which a series of pores would supply the slime compound.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] The compound would turn into a viscous slime on contact with water and coat the mesh.
[src:biofouling/anti-fouling-paint] The slime would constantly slough off, carrying away micro-organisms and barnacle larvae.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] Athenaeus himself states that he was the author of a treatise on the *thratta*, a type of fish mentioned by Archippus and other comic poets, and of a history of the Syrian kings.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] Of his works, only the fifteen-volume *Deipnosophistae* mostly survives.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The *Deipnosophistae*, which means 'dinner-table philosophers', survives in fifteen books.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The first two books, and parts of the third, eleventh and fifteenth, are extant only in epitome, but otherwise the work seems to be complete.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] It is an immense store-house of information, chiefly on matters connected with famous cooks, dining, but also containing remarks on music, songs, dances, philosophy, games, courtesans, and luxury.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] Nearly 800 writers and 2,500 separate works are referred to by Athenaeus; one of his characters (not necessarily to be identified with the historical author himself) boasts of having read 800 plays of Athenian Middle Comedy alone.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] Were it not for Athenaeus, much valuable information about the ancient world would be missing, and many ancient Greek authors such as Archestratus would be almost entirely unknown.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] Book XIII, for example, is an important source for the study of sexuality in classical and Hellenistic Greece, and a rare fragment of Theognetus' work survives in 3.63.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The *Deipnosophistae* professes to be an account given by an individual named Athenaeus to his friend Timocrates of a banquet held at the house of Larensius (Λαρήνσιος; in Latin: Larensis), a wealthy book-collector and patron of the arts.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] It is thus a dialogue within a dialogue, after the manner of Plato, but the conversation extends to enormous length.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The topics for discussion generally arise from the course of the dinner itself, but extend to literary and historical matters of every description, including abstruse points of grammar.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The guests supposedly quote from memory.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The actual sources of the material preserved in the *Deipnosophistae* remain obscure, but much of it probably comes at second hand from early scholars.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The twenty-four named guests include individuals called Galen and Ulpian, but they are all probably fictitious personages, and the majority take no part in the conversation.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] If the character Ulpian is identical with the famous jurist, the *Deipnosophistae* may have been written after his death in 223; but the jurist was murdered by the Praetorian Guard, whereas Ulpian in Athenaeus dies a natural death.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The complete version of the text, with the gaps noted above, is preserved in only one manuscript, conventionally referred to as A.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The epitomized version of the text is preserved in two manuscripts, conventionally known as C and E.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The standard edition of the text is Olson's Teubner.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The standard numbering is drawn largely from Casaubon.
[src:biofouling/athenaeus] The encyclopaedist and author Sir Thomas Browne wrote a short essay upon Athenaeus which reflects a revived interest in the *Banquet of the Learned* amongst scholars during the 17th century following its publication in 1612 by the Classical scholar Isaac Casaubon.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Anti-fouling is the ability of specifically designed materials (such as toxic biocide paints, or non-toxic paints) to remove or prevent biofouling.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The buildup of biofouling on marine vessels poses a significant problem.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In some instances, the hull structure and propulsion systems can be damaged.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The accumulation of biofoulers on hulls can increase both the hydrodynamic volume of a vessel and the hydrodynamic friction, leading to increased drag of up to 60%.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The drag increase has been seen to decrease speeds by up to 10%, which can require up to a 40% increase in fuel to compensate.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] With fuel typically comprising up to half of marine transport costs, antifouling methods save the shipping industry a considerable amount of money.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Further, increased fuel use due to biofouling contributes to adverse environmental effects and is predicted to increase emissions of carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide between 38% and 72% by 2020, respectively.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biofouling organisms are highly diverse, and extend far beyond the attachment of barnacles and seaweeds.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] According to some estimates, over 1,700 species comprising over 4,000 organisms are responsible for biofouling.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biofouling is divided into **microfouling**—biofilm formation and bacterial adhesion—and **macrofouling**—attachment of larger organisms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Due to the distinct chemistry and biology that determine what prevents them from settling, organisms are also classified as hard- or soft-fouling types.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Calcareous (hard) fouling organisms include barnacles, encrusting bryozoans, mollusks such as zebra mussels, and polychaete and other tube worms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Examples of non-calcareous (soft) fouling organisms are seaweed, hydroids, algae, and biofilm "slime".
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Together, these organisms form a fouling community.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Marine fouling is typically described as following four stages of ecosystem development.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Within the first minute the van der Waals interaction causes the submerged surface to be covered with a conditioning film of organic polymers.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In the next 24 hours, this layer allows the process of bacterial adhesion to occur, with both diatoms and bacteria (e.g.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] *Vibrio alginolyticus*, *Pseudomonas putrefaciens*) attaching, initiating the formation of a biofilm.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] By the end of the first week, the rich nutrients and ease of attachment into the biofilm allow secondary colonizers of spores of macroalgae (e.g.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] *Enteromorpha intestinalis*, *Ulothrix*) and sessile protozoans (e.g.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] *Vorticella*, *Zoothamnium* sp.) to attach themselves.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Within two to three weeks, the tertiary colonizers—the macrofoulers—have attached.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These include tunicates, mollusks, and sessile cnidarians.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Governments and industry spend more than US$5.7 billion annually to prevent and control marine biofouling.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biofouling occurs everywhere but is most significant economically to the shipping industries, since fouling on a ship's hull significantly increases drag, reducing the overall hydrodynamic performance of the vessel, and increases the fuel consumption.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biofouling is also found in almost all circumstances where water-based liquids are in contact with other materials.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Industrially important impacts are on the maintenance of mariculture, membrane systems (*e.g.*, membrane bioreactors and reverse osmosis spiral wound membranes) and cooling water cycles of large industrial equipment and power stations.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biofouling can occur in oil pipelines carrying oils with entrained water, especially those carrying used oils, cutting oils, oils rendered water-soluble through emulsification, and hydraulic oils.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Other mechanisms impacted by biofouling include microelectrochemical drug delivery devices, papermaking and pulp industry machines, underwater instruments, fire protection system piping, and sprinkler system nozzles.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In groundwater wells, biofouling buildup can limit recovery flow rates, as is the case in the exterior and interior of ocean-laying pipes where fouling is often removed with a tube cleaning process.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Besides interfering with mechanisms, biofouling also occurs on the surfaces of living marine organisms, when it is known as epibiosis.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Medical devices often include fan-cooled heat sinks, to cool their electronic components.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] While these systems sometimes include HEPA filters to collect microbes, some pathogens do pass through these filters, collect inside the device and are eventually blown out and infect other patients.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Devices used in operating rooms rarely include fans, so as to minimize the chance of transmission.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Also, medical equipment, HVAC units, high-end computers, swimming pools, drinking-water systems and other products that utilize liquid lines run the risk of biofouling as biological growth occurs inside them.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Historically, the focus of attention has been the severe impact due to biofouling on the speed of marine vessels.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In some instances the hull structure and propulsion systems can become damaged.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Over time, the accumulation of biofoulers on hulls increases both the hydrodynamic volume of a vessel and the frictional effects leading to increased drag of up to 60% The additional drag can decrease speeds up to 10%, which can require up to a 40% increase in fuel to compensate.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] With fuel typically comprising up to half of marine transport costs, biofouling is estimated to cost the US Navy alone around $1 billion per year in increased fuel usage, maintenance and biofouling control measures.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Increased fuel use due to biofouling contributes to adverse environmental effects and is predicted to increase emissions of carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide between 38 and 72 percent by 2020.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biofouling also impacts aquaculture, increasing production and management costs, while decreasing product value.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Fouling communities may compete with shellfish directly for food resources, impede the procurement of food and oxygen by reducing water flow around shellfish, or interfere with the operational opening of their valves.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Consequently, stock affected by biofouling can experience reduced growth, condition and survival, with subsequent negative impacts on farm productivity.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Although many methods of removal exist, they often impact the cultured species, sometimes more so than the fouling organisms themselves.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Shipping companies have historically relied on scheduled biofouler removal to keep such accretions to a manageable level.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] However, the rate of accretion can vary widely between vessels and operating conditions, so predicting acceptable intervals between cleanings is difficult.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] LED manufacturers have developed a range of UVC (250–280 nm) equipment that can detect biofouling buildup, and can even prevent it.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Fouling detection relies on the biomass' property of fluorescence.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] All microorganisms contain natural intracellular fluorophores, which radiate in the UV range when excited.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] At UV-range wavelengths, such fluorescence arises from three aromatic amino acids—tyrosine, phenylalanine, and tryptophan.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The easiest to detect is tryptophan, which radiates at 350 nm when irradiated at 280 nm.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In 2023, the International Maritime Organization (IMO) adopted 'Guidelines for the control and management of ships' biofouling to minimize the transfer of invasive aquatic species'.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In April 2025, the IMO agreed to develop a legally binding framework for controlling and managing ships’ biofouling to reduce the accumulation of marine organisms on the hulls of ships and thereby reduce the transfer of invasive aquatic species.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Controlling ship's biofouling also improves the environmental efficiency of ships by reducing drag resistance.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Non-toxic anti-sticking coatings prevent attachment of microorganisms thus negating the use of biocides.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These coatings are usually based on organic polymers.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] There are two classes of non-toxic anti-fouling coatings.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The most common class relies on low friction and low surface energies.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Low surface energies result in hydrophobic surfaces.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These coatings create a smooth surface, which can prevent attachment of larger microorganisms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] For example, fluoropolymers and silicone coatings are commonly used.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These coatings are ecologically inert but have problems with mechanical strength and long-term stability.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Specifically, after days biofilms (slime) can coat the surfaces, which buries the chemical activity and allows microorganisms to attach.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The current standard for these coatings is polydimethylsiloxane, or PDMS, which consists of a non-polar backbone made of repeating units of silicon and oxygen atoms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The non-polarity of PDMS allows for biomolecules to readily adsorb to its surface in order to lower interfacial energy.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] However, PDMS also has a low modulus of elasticity that allows for the release of fouling organisms at speeds of greater than 20 knots.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The dependence of effectiveness on vessel speed prevents use of PDMS on slow-moving ships or those that spend significant amounts of time in port.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The second class of non-toxic antifouling coatings are hydrophilic coatings.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] They rely on high amounts of hydration in order to increase the energetic penalty of removing water for proteins and microorganisms to attach.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The most common examples of these coatings are based on highly hydrated zwitterions, such as glycine betaine and sulfobetaine.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These coatings are also low-friction, but are considered by some to be superior to hydrophobic surfaces because they prevent bacteria attachment, preventing biofilm formation.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These coatings are not yet commercially available and are being designed as part of a larger effort by the Office of Naval Research to develop environmentally safe biomimetic ship coatings.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biocides are chemical substances that kill or deter microorganisms responsible for biofouling.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The biocide is typically applied as a paint, i.e. through physical adsorption.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The biocides prevent the formation of biofilms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Other biocides are toxic to larger organisms in biofouling, such as algae.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Formerly, the so-called tributyltin (TBT) compounds were used as biocides (and thus anti-fouling agents).
[src:biofouling/biofouling] TBTs are toxic to both microorganisms and larger aquatic organisms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The international maritime community has phased out the use of organotin-based coatings.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Replacing organotin compounds is dichlorooctylisothiazolinone.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] This compound, however, also suffers from broad toxicity to marine organisms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Ultrasonic transducers may be mounted in or around the hull of small to medium-sized boats.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Research has shown these systems can help reduce fouling, by initiating bursts of ultrasonic waves through the hull medium to the surrounding water, killing or denaturing the algae and other microorganisms that form the beginning of the fouling sequence.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The systems cannot work on wooden-hulled boats, or boats with a soft-cored composite material, such as wood or foam.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The systems have been loosely based on technology proven to control algae blooms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Pulsed laser irradiation is commonly used against diatoms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Plasma pulse technology is effective against zebra mussels and works by stunning or killing the organisms with microsecond-duration energizing of the water with high-voltage electricity.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Similarly, another method shown to be effective against algae buildups bounces brief high-energy acoustic pulses down pipes.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Regimens to periodically use heat to treat exchanger equipment and pipes have been successfully used to remove mussels from power plant cooling systems using water at 105 °F (40 °C) for 30 minutes.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The medical industry utilizes a variety of energy methods to address bioburden issues associated with biofouling.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Autoclaving typically involves heating a medical device to 121 °C (249 °F) for 15–20 minutes.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Ultrasonic cleaning, UV light, and chemical wipe-down or immersion can also be used for different types of devices.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] UVC irradiation is a noncontact, nonchemical solution that can be used across a range of instruments.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Radiation in the UVC range prevents biofilm formation by deactivating the DNA in bacteria, viruses, and other microbes.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Preventing biofilm formation prevents larger organisms from attaching themselves to the instrument and eventually rendering it inoperable.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Biofouling, especially of ships, has been a problem for as long as humans have been sailing the oceans.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The earliest attestations of attempts to counter fouling, and thus also the earliest attestation of knowledge of it, is the use of pitch and copper plating as anti-fouling solutions that were attributed to ancient seafaring nations, such as the Phoenicians and Carthaginians (1500–300 BC).
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Wax, tar and asphaltum have been used since early times.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] An Aramaic record dating from 412 BC tells of a ship's bottom being coated with a mixture of arsenic, oil and sulphur.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In *Deipnosophistae*, Athenaeus described the anti-fouling efforts taken in the construction of the great ship of Hieron of Syracuse (died 467 BC).
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Before the 18th century, various anti-fouling techniques were used, with three main substances employed: "White stuff", a mixture of train oil (whale oil), rosin and sulfur; "Black stuff", a mixture of tar and pitch; and "Brown stuff", which was simply sulfur added to Black stuff.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In many of these cases, the purpose of these treatments is ambiguous.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] There is dispute whether many of these treatments were actual anti-fouling techniques, or whether, when they were used in conjunction with lead and wood sheathing, they were simply intended to combat wood-boring shipworms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In 1708, Charles Perry suggested copper sheathing explicitly as an anti-fouling device but the first experiments were not made until 1761 with the sheathing of HMS Alarm, after which the bottoms and sides of several ships' keels and false keels were sheathed with copper plates.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The copper performed well in protecting the hull from invasion by worm, and in preventing the growth of weed, for when in contact with water, the copper produced a poisonous film, composed mainly of oxychloride, that deterred these marine creatures.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Furthermore, as this film was slightly soluble, it gradually washed away, leaving no way for marine life to attach itself to the ship.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] From about 1770, the Royal Navy set about coppering the bottoms of the entire fleet and continued to the end of the use of wooden ships.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The process was so successful that the term *copper-bottomed* came to mean something that was highly dependable or risk free.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] With the rise of iron hulls in the 19th century, copper sheathing could no longer be used due to its galvanic corrosive interaction with iron.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Anti-fouling paints were tried, and in 1860, the first practical paint to gain widespread use was introduced in Liverpool and was referred to as "McIness" hot plastic paint.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These treatments had a short service life, were expensive, and relatively ineffective by modern standards.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] By the mid-twentieth century, copper oxide-based paints could keep a ship out of drydock for as much as 18 months, or as little as 12 in tropical waters.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The shorter service life was due to rapid leaching of the toxicant, and chemical conversion into less toxic salts, which accumulated as a crust that would inhibit further leaching of active cuprous oxide from the layer under the crust.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The 1960s brought a breakthrough, with self-polishing paints that slowly hydrolyze, slowly releasing toxins.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These paints employed organotin chemistry ("tin-based") biotoxins such as tributyltin oxide (TBT) and were effective for up to four years.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] These biotoxins were subsequently banned by the International Maritime Organization when they were found to be very toxic to diverse organisms.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] TBT in particular has been described as the most toxic pollutant ever deliberately released in the ocean.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] As an alternative to organotin toxins, there has been renewed interest in copper as the active agent in ablative or self polishing paints, with reported service lives up to 5 years; yet also other methods that do not involve coatings.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Modern adhesives permit application of copper alloys to steel hulls without creating galvanic corrosion.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] However, copper alone is not impervious to diatom and algae fouling.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Some studies indicate that copper may also present an unacceptable environmental impact.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Study of biofouling began in the early 19th century with Davy's experiments linking the effectiveness of copper to its solute rate.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] In the 1930s microbiologist Claude ZoBell showed that the attachment of organisms is preceded by the adsorption of organic compounds now referred to as extracellular polymeric substances.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] One trend of research is the study of the relationship between wettability and anti-fouling effectiveness.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Another trend is the study of living organisms as the inspiration for new functional materials.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] For example, the mechanisms used by marine animals to inhibit biofouling on their skin.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] A study of the biotoxins used by organisms has revealed several effective compounds, some of which are more powerful than synthetic compounds.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Bufalin, a bufotoxin, was found to be over 100 times as potent as TBT, and over 6,000 times more effective in anti-settlement activity against barnacles.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] One approach to antifouling entails coating surfaces with polyethylene glycol (PEG).
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Growing chains of PEG on surfaces is challenging.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The resolution to this problem may come from understanding the mechanisms by which mussels adhere to solid surfaces in marine environments.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] Mussels utilize adhesive proteins, or MAPs.
[src:biofouling/biofouling] The service life of PEG coatings is also doubtful.
